title: For Sale:  PTR-91 fully dressed
postcontent:
Sorry for the HK labeling, Armslist does not have a selection for PTR Industries. This is a lightly used (<100 rounds) PTR-91 GI, with OD green furniture and the naval polymer trigger group. It is THE HK-91 clone, manufactured on HK machinery. Only difference is a hammer forged match grade barrel instead of HKs mil spec.

Comes with everything pictured (plus the original case and manual):

- 24x 20-round HK magazines (4 new, 20 surplus)
- THREE different forends
  -- The original OD (on right)
  -- A UTG milled aluminum tri-rail with rail covers (left, about $40)
  -- An original HK black wide forend with integrated bipod (hkparts.net has just the forend for $200+, with bipod usually retails for $600)
- Factory HK rear sight adjustment tool ($50 on hkparts.net)
- PTR Industries bolt carrier assembly tool ($25)
- Barska cantilevered scope rings
- Simple 3-9x40 Banner/Bushnell scope ($125)

So I have about $2000 sum total in this. But it sits in the back of my safe, and that's no way to treat this gun. Will sell entire package for $1400 cash. Trades are welcome, though there's not much I'm really hunting for. I'm not really interested in shotguns or 1911s, just FYI. And cash trumps all other offers.

Just a little on the GI and PTR: the GI, unlike earlier PTR-91s, is not fickle with ammo. It will eat anything you feed it, and its bolt is huge and rugged. PTR was based in Farmington CT, but announced in the Hartford Courant that, due to that, ahem, esteemed state's new gun laws it would return the "up yours" they received by moving. They just announced that they will be moving just north of Myrtle Beach. According to Investors Business Daily, their production run annually increased from 2000 in 2011 to 4400 in 2012, and they are trying to produce 10,000 this year. Nevertheless, they have standing orders for 56,000 rifles - in other words, IF they meet their production goals, they will be back ordered for 5 1/2 years!

I just replaced all the Coil Packs, spark plugs, Idler and tensioner pulley, ac compressor, fuel filter, air filter, belt and just had a oil change with the 5,000 mile oil added for extra protection. Mechanically the car is solid, its a P71. We all know these cars are used by police and taxi services because the are extremely reliable. My company gave me a work car, I have my brand new Chrysler and a 79 Z28 + wife's car and we live in a town home with limited parking. The body is solid, there is rust starting to pop out on the lips of the fender wells, and on the lower part of the drivers fender. The trunk does have to plugs and the roof has one. It has the black cop rims with the chrome center caps, and the black grill. The paint is still bright, the spot light works and its fun driving because all the idiots that drive slow in the left hand lane surly move out of your way when your coming up behind them. Great if your running late. 

The car is what it is nothing special, but one heck of a reliable car that will run for countless miles. Everything that goes wrong with them around 100,000 has been replaced before it could go bad. I think its a lot easier to invest the money in parts before they break then deal with the breakdown itself. 

3,000 OBO like I said no longer need, and its taken up space, but that does not mean I am hurting for money and need to sell it, so be reasonable
